I made a cheap power supply which can provide three different voltages. With cheap of DC-DC stepdown converter modules. The downside of these cheap converters, they are not very proof to short circuits. As I found out myself….
The cover is made of 3 mm PMMA, plexiglass. Is was cut on a laser-cutter. The design was draw with Solidworks and exported as dxf-file. This format was compatible with the laser-cutter.
I soldered 4 mm banana plugs. I use standard voltage displays. These have power from the test leads. The downside of this is that for voltages under 3 Volt the display powers down. However I need for my project mostly 3.3 V, 5 V, 9 V or 12 V. title: Open-mic Case for Lightdow Action Camera

description.text:
Too cheap to buy a GoPro, I bought a knock-off style Lightdow product from Amazon. All of the gear that came in my order for mounting it was practically the same as GoPro, but the camera itself followed a different form-factor. Smaller and ports and buttons in different places.

Since the original use was to take some video in a pool, the waterproof case was great. But when we took a trip to Disneyland, I wanted to have something with easier access to buttons, screen, and, more importantly, an uncovered mic.

So I designed this little thing. After several failures to create something that was sturdy enough to take some abuse, I settled on this design. I created the shell then used some GoPro mount code I found in another SCAD file here on Thingiverse and merged it with the bottom.

The result is a fit that secures the camera well, allows for easy access to all ports and buttons, and allows the camera to easily be removed or inserted without problems.

To get the two-colors, I used Jetty's Gen4 Interface code and stopped at a Z-position of +.84, because I am printing at a layer height of 0.28.

this is, as my friend called it, a "hate child". A few years ago i built a prusa i2 and loved that the frame was made out of 5/16 rod i could get at a hardware store, however the bed was heavy and the y motor is overdriven to move it at a similar speed to the x carriage, furthermore there are 2 motors for the z axis witch, considering it has the highest gear ratio i saw as a unnecessary $14. this printer is a combination of the makerbot and prusa i2. it utilizes the cheap, easy to access parts of a prusa but has the movement of a maker-bot.

this printer is partially parametric and you can use the supplied excel sheet to show the required rod lengths
the parts required are:
12 lm8uu linear bearings
7 rollerblade bearings
8mm (or 5/16) smooth rod
8mm (or 5/16) threaded rod
a whole lotta nuts (about .5 lb)

title: Yet Another TriGorilla MOSFET Mounting Plate

description.text:
My Maker Select V2 started shutting itself down once I started trying to run the bed at 80, so I ordered one of the TriGorilla MOSFET relays from Amazon and overpaid to get it same day:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01HCVJ3K2/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o01_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

From the picture, I was thinking it would be about an inch by two, but the thing is huge like 2 1/2" X 3 1/2”, which is "cool" because it has a huge heatsink :)

So naturally I came here to see what others have done, and after looking at several designs came up with some requirements that none seemed to meet, at least that I could(n't) find.
1) Mounted internally.
2) Mounted with screws, no velcro or double-sided tape.
3) No drilling holes in the Controller box.

So I designed this plate to use the two M5 screws that are on top of the controller, that are apparently there to optionally mount the spool holder there. I am satisfied with how it turned out as it just fits next to the motherboard, ends up right next to an air vent, lines up the inputs with the motherboard, and the outputs with the power supply.

There are M5 threads in the two holes that go thru, and M3 threads in the four mounting standoffs as I had a ton left over after doing the Z brace mod. It helps to run the screws thru each hole to help "tap" them out before assembling. Unscrew the two M5 screws out until they clear the nuts that are pressed into the inside of the case, then hold the plate tight against those and screw them back in. Try to make sure they engage the threads, rather than push the plate away so it will pull up tight against them. Then attach the MOSFET to the four M3 standoffs (or attach it first as the two M3 screws next to the case are somewhat hard to get to if done after as I did).

I made the prototype 4mm thick to give lots of material for the M5 screws to bite, but that added a lot of time to the print so I thinned it down to 2mm thick with a 4mm edge and put some shells around just the M5 threads where it is needed which also protects the ends of the M5's from ever touching the bottom of the MOSFET board (although the M3 standoffs should already give plenty of clearance).

As can be seen in the pics, I haven't fully re-assembled everything and ran this configuration yet as my printer's motherboard died right after making the prototype, so I consider this still a work in progress but wanted to go ahead and share it now. Hope you like!

UPDATE: 5/8/2017
V2 - I decided that I actually want to mount the spool holder on the controller box, and don't want to use those screws to hold up the plate. So, I redesigned the plate to use the motherboard mounts, and added cutouts to save some time and materials.

Here is the Tinkercad:
V1 - https://tinkercad.com/things/777ke42B5AX
V2 - https://tinkercad.com/things/9xUK5DuHTTp

UPDATE: 5/14/2007
While finally reassembling my controller box, found that the motherboard standoff were about 1mm too tall. I just filed mine down, but revised the model so those standoffs are 7.4mm high.

title: Soft Mount for Flight Controller (FC) and Power Distribution Board (PDB)

description.text:
I wanted to design an option for soft mounting my flight controller and power distribution board. These are intended to be printed with a semiflex filament. M3 screws will fit through the holes. I recommend using M3 nylon screws.

SoftMount_PDBv2 - this model has 4 screw columns. It can be used for a Power Distribution Board, 4-in-1 ESC, or a Flight Controller. Since it only has 4 screw columns, it may still transfer some vibrations- but this option is easy to mount, as it will go directly into your frame (assuming it is for a 36x36mm board, with 30.5x30.5 mounts- this is what most F3/F4 flight controllers, such as the Naze 32 are).

SoftMount_FC_PDBv2 - this model has 8 screw columns. 4 of the columns are intended to be mounted to your frame, and the other 4 are used to mount your board. When using this mount, you will need to update your flight controller configuration so it knows that your board is rotated 45 degrees.

Use M3 nylon screws and nuts to secure the screws. You will need a screw long enough to go through the columns for the flight controller. You will need a longer screw for your frame (depending on frame thickness). For the flight controller, I think a 10mm 3M screw should work, and give you enough for a nut, but it would be good to double check.

Several parts I've designed for one of my favorite frames...

3 position camera mount: Positionable @ 25, 40, and 55 degrees. Fits HS1177, RunCam swift, etc. Accepts lenses with ~17mm outside diameter. (stock RunCam lenses probably wont work)

Fixed camera mounts: These are slightly tweaked versions of Josh from Flynoceros original designs. I use an HS1177 and wanted a 25 degree mount that was compatible with my camera/lens. Later made a 40 degree version as well. These are designed to also work with my tray designs.

Battery/Protective Trays: A few variants of these. Original design was for top mounted battery w/Rx antenna holes. Newer version has mount for Unify pigtail included. Another version has same Unify hole, but with a notch that matches up w/ my GoPro Session mount. I found the matched notches helps with the session mount from sliding around.

GoPro Session mount: Universal design with tie wrap holes will fit on any flat mounting surface. Also a version with a notch that works in conjunction with my tray design to stop camera from sliding around.

VTx mount: Designed this to fit between the vertical frame rails on the Canis. Uses the frame bolts and frame notches as mounting support in addition to a tie wrap near base of VTx and antenna nut. Designed specifically for Lumenier Vtx, but will definitely accommodate models with similar dimensions.

description.text:
This is my second spinning top. It isn't as polished as my first top but I've integrated basic aerodynamics to see if it will improve spin-time.

This is a clockwise spinning top. Although, it will spin counter-clockwise but the aerodynamics effects will be void.

This top uses the same 3/8" nuts and 1/4" ball bearing as my previous top. The purpose of the holes under the nuts was to be able to remove them easily for re-purposing purposes, but due to the ducted design of this top, I removed the bottom holes to prevent airflow from coming back up through the nuts and disturbing the flow. So a 3/8" screw will be required for extraction on this part.

This part is not perfect. There are some parts that didn't print perfectly using a 0.4mm nozzle so a 0.3mm or 0.2mmm nozzle is recommended.

I've printed mine at 0.4mm x 0.2mm thickness. 3 shells and 20% infill. My nuts may not be balanced so I got a little wobble.

In case anyone is wondering, this model is in millimeters, so scale accordingly.

Don't expect the aerodynamics to be mind-blowing. However, you can feel an extra breeze coming from the bottom of the top. Perhaps I'll add a mini jet engine in the next design.

Enjoy.

description.text:
This is a "bearing" for fidget spinners. It was modeled to be the same size as the 608 bearings commonly used in fidget spinners. The center hole is 8mm, so you should still be able to use thumb pads. The outer diameter is 22mm and therefore should pop into any spinner you might want to put it in. There are 3 different versions. A loose version (called "bearing"), a tighter version ("bearing-tighter"), and a version with 4 cutouts ("bearing-slots").

There is always room for improvement.

description.text:
LiPo is a short way of saying Lithium Polymer batteries, Lipo batteries are packaged generally in prismatic pouch made of some plastic polymers. These batteries are known for their exceptional "boost discharge capabilities". Lithium polymer batteries are labeled nnC where nn is a number. For example a 1000mAH Lipo battery with 50C label is capable of supplying 50 Amperes of current for a fixed time. Lipo is lighter in weight and hence is more energy dense than Lithium Ion batteries. You will find these batteries in toys where weight is a constraint e.g. flying toys for kids, toy quad-copters, heli, airplanes etc. But what is the basic construction of a LiPo battery? The lipo battery construction is as follows:

Anode: aluminum foil current collector. Metal oxide active material (NMC, NCA, LCO, LFP). Binder (PVDF - Polyvinyladine Fluoride). Conductive carbon (Acetylene black, Vulcan , graphite )

Cathode: copper current collector. Graphite active material. Binder (PVDF, or CMC/SBR -- carboxymethyl cellulose and styrene butadiene rubber). Conductive carbon.

Separator: polypropylene film, ionically conductive but electrically insulating, e.g. Celgard

Electrolyte: carbonate solvents including ethylene carbonate (EC), dimethyl carbonate (DMC), diethyl carbonate (DEC), propylene carbonate (PC). Lithium salt, eg lithium hexafluorophosphate (LiPF6)

Pouch material: aluminum with polymer coating.

Tabs: aluminum cathode tab, nickel anode tab

Construction: double sided anode and cathode sheets are stacked and wrapped in separator, sometimes in Z-fold pattern. Anode and cathode Electrode stack tabs are ultrasonically welded together, placing them in series. Anode and cathode tabs are further welded to external tabs (Al or Ni, see above). Welded stack is packaged in 3-side sealed pouch, filled with electrolyte, then 4th side is sealed in vacuum pouch step.

description.text:
This is version 2 of the filament mount for the SeeMeCNC Hacker H2 printer. It aligns the filament spool with the EZRstruder without having to have the filament reel just sitting on the table or bench. The same spool tube is used in both versions, just the clip and the mount itself have changed.

My previous version only works with the Rostock arms on the Hacker H2. The Orion arms would hit this mount especially when doing a delta calibration. This version solves that problem.

The spool holder remains at the same height as the other version but actually locks on the Y tower at a lower point than the Y carriage can hit. It includes a clip which allows it to lock onto the Y tower of the printer.

The tube has an angle on it with cutouts allowing for a solid but easy fit. Breaking it into 3 pieces allows it to be printer on the Hacker H2 as well.

The yellow picture shows how it needs to be setup on your build plate which will allow it to print without any supports needed. The main mount piece DOES have a support built into it for one small area.

Due to the thinness of the clip that goes around the extrusion, make sure you use plenty of hairspray, glue, or whatever you use to get it to stick well to your bed so that those areas don't lift.

I printed this in Inland Blue PETG and it was designed in GeoMagic Design.

Notes:

I printed three using a LulzBot Mini in ABS using the standard settings, and 100% fill. It is designed to print on the side so as to maximize the thread's axial strength and create a clean hole for the nut. In the side-orientation the design has a little bit of overhang, so the model includes a disposable support for that portion. The model's ACME-thread diameters are oversized 9%, as shown in the cross-section, to accommodate plastic shrinkage and tolerance.

I modeled this part using SketchUp. That was tricky because the vice screw uses an ACME 1/2-10 double-start or "fast-travel" thread (and I didn't know anything about either when I started this project). I am indebted to Jim Hamilton who posted a cool YouTube video on how to model ACME threads using SketchUp. And, of course, I wouldn't have been able to do it without the Machinery's Handbook for providing the thread dimensions.

I made this 60mm fan mount for my Replicator 2X to stir the air inside the unit. Helps quite a bit with air circulation and print quality. I used 60mm x 15mm fans, and an area of Velcro on the back wall to hold the fans. Velcro allows me to reposition and experiment a little with placement.

Print it, put velcro on the feet, attach to rear wall of Replicator 2X. Check clearance with other moving parts in the system. I used "industrial strength" velcro just because I had it laying around. Regular Velcro will probably be fine. Check it once in awhile to make sure it's not coming loose. Cleaning the feet with acetone first will help velcro tape stick well. You could also drill holes in the back of your machine for permanent mounting.
